":"<strong>New Baskerville</strong><br/>Probably the best serif typeface ever designed. Not showy but full of confidence, Baskerville is known as a transitional serif typeface and was originally designed in 1757 by John Baskerville (1706–1775) in Birmingham. A transitional typeface is positioned between the old-style typefaces of <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Caslon\">William Caslon</a>, and the modern styles of Bodoni and Didot. Since then many versions have been produced by various type foundries including this popular New Baskerville version. What really makes it work is the way the roman and italic versions are successful whether used together or individually","credit":"Photograph: Domenic Lippa","source":"Domenic Lippa","width":"68","height":"68","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987131673/New-Baskerville-011-thumb-2320.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"gu-image-417118802","imageType":"Photograph"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-417118741","relation":"gallery","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987117598/DIN-1451-003.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"10 best: DIN 1451","caption":"<strong>DIN 1451</strong><br/>Designed in 1931 for the German standards body DIN – Deutsches Institut für Normung (German Institute for Standardisation) – it looks and behaves as if it had been produced today. It extols all of the principles of the Bauhaus and has not dated in any way. It has two strong characteristics – first, it is a condensed font, meaning on a very simplistic level that it creates a strong mass when used as text and therefore the type can become more of a shape. Second, it has a quietly beautiful rounded detail, which makes it feel like it was designed for the age of computers, but still retains a gentleness","credit":"Photograph: Domenic Lippa","source":"Domenic Lippa","width":"453","height":"428","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987117598/DIN-1451-003.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"gu-image-417118741","imageType":"Photograph"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987117598/DIN-1451-003-thumb-5774.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"10 best: DIN 1451","caption":"<strong>DIN 1451</strong><br/>Designed in 1931 for the German standards body DIN – Deutsches Institut für Normung (German Institute for Standardisation) – it looks and behaves as if it had been produced today. It extols all of the principles of the Bauhaus and has not dated in any way. It has two strong characteristics – first, it is a condensed font, meaning on a very simplistic level that it creates a strong mass when used as text and therefore the type can become more of a shape. Second, it has a quietly beautiful rounded detail, which makes it feel like it was designed for the age of computers, but still retains a gentleness","credit":"Photograph: Domenic Lippa","source":"Domenic Lippa","width":"68","height":"68","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987117598/DIN-1451-003-thumb-5774.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"gu-image-417118741","imageType":"Photograph"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-417118743","relation":"gallery","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987119018/Franklin-Gothic-004.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"10 best: Franklin Gothic","caption":"<strong>Franklin Gothic</strong><br/>Produced by the American type designer Morris Fuller Benton (1872–1948) in 1902, it reflects everything that America was aspiring to and would become – confident, bold and expressive. It’s American through and through. The bold version I think is best: its blackness is just so powerful. Franklin Gothic has more character than other realist sans serif fonts. I’ve always believed Franklin Gothic works best next to a more subtle, sensitive font. The best example was seen in the groundbreaking work by the American-based French designer <a href=\"http://www.baron-baron.com/flash/2/master.html\">Fabien Baron</a> for Vogue Italia in the late 1980s","credit":"Photograph: Domenic Lippa","source":"Domenic Lippa","width":"453","height":"428","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987119018/Franklin-Gothic-004.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"gu-image-417118743","imageType":"Photograph"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987119018/Franklin-Gothic-004-thumb-8738.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"10 best: Franklin Gothic","caption":"<strong>Franklin Gothic</strong><br/>Produced by the American type designer Morris Fuller Benton (1872–1948) in 1902, it reflects everything that America was aspiring to and would become – confident, bold and expressive. It’s American through and through. The bold version I think is best: its blackness is just so powerful. Franklin Gothic has more character than other realist sans serif fonts. I’ve always believed Franklin Gothic works best next to a more subtle, sensitive font. The best example was seen in the groundbreaking work by the American-based French designer <a href=\"http://www.baron-baron.com/flash/2/master.html\">Fabien Baron</a> for Vogue Italia in the late 1980s","credit":"Photograph: Domenic Lippa","source":"Domenic Lippa","width":"68","height":"68","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987119018/Franklin-Gothic-004-thumb-8738.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"gu-image-417118743","imageType":"Photograph"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-417118793","relation":"gallery","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987120607/HTF-Didot-005.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"10 best: HTF Didot","caption":"<strong>HTF Didot</strong><br/>This is a revival font. I could have chosen Bodoni, which I also love, but Didot gets the nod over its Italian sibling. However, it’s this particular cut by the type designers <a href=\"http://www.typography.com/\">Jonathan Hoefler and Toby Frere-Jones</a> that I think is something near to perfection. It was created for the Harper’s Bazaar magazine in the 1980s for the aforementioned Fabien Baron. It just feels like a fashion font – effortlessly beautiful but honed and crafted. But beware – it is tricky to use as it’s so delicate. It needs to be handled with care as the characters have extremes of thicks and hairline thins. It’s simply beautiful","credit":"Photograph: Domenic Lippa","source":"Domenic Lippa","width":"453","height":"428","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987120607/HTF-Didot-005.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"gu-image-417118793","imageType":"Photograph"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987120607/HTF-Didot-005-thumb-6998.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"10 best: HTF Didot","caption":"<strong>HTF Didot</strong><br/>This is a revival font. I could have chosen Bodoni, which I also love, but Didot gets the nod over its Italian sibling. However, it’s this particular cut by the type designers <a href=\"http://www.typography.com/\">Jonathan Hoefler and Toby Frere-Jones</a> that I think is something near to perfection. It was created for the Harper’s Bazaar magazine in the 1980s for the aforementioned Fabien Baron. It just feels like a fashion font – effortlessly beautiful but honed and crafted. But beware – it is tricky to use as it’s so delicate. It needs to be handled with care as the characters have extremes of thicks and hairline thins. It’s simply beautiful","credit":"Photo