azine, it is very much an American font in that its design was inspired by the lettering found on the architecture of New York City","credit":"Photograph: Domenic Lippa","source":"Domenic Lippa","width":"68","height":"68","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987123141/Gotham-006-thumb-4359.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"gu-image-417118788","imageType":"Photograph"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-417118798","relation":"gallery","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987124374/Knockout-007.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"10 best: Knockout","caption":"<strong>Knockout</strong><br/>Knockout gets my vote almost just for its name. All the variants are based on different boxing weights. It is another design from the Hoefler and Frere-Jones type foundry, consisting of a family of 32 different sans serif weights. Knockout’s nine-width, four-weight family offers a range of options that cannot be achieved with even the best modern sans serifs. Most fonts begin their life with maybe just a regular, bold and italic version. If a design is successful then more weights are added as required over the years. Knockout was created as a family from the outset and therefore has achieved instant integration and balance","credit":"Photograph: Domenic Lippa","source":"Domenic Lippa","width":"453","height":"428","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987124374/Knockout-007.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"gu-image-417118798","imageType":"Photograph"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987124374/Knockout-007-thumb-9427.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"10 best: Knockout","caption":"<strong>Knockout</strong><br/>Knockout gets my vote almost just for its name. All the variants are based on different boxing weights. It is another design from the Hoefler and Frere-Jones type foundry, consisting of a family of 32 different sans serif weights. Knockout’s nine-width, four-weight family offers a range of options that cannot be achieved with even the best modern sans serifs. Most fonts begin their life with maybe just a regular, bold and italic version. If a design is successful then more weights are added as required over the years. Knockout was created as a family from the outset and therefore has achieved instant integration and balance","credit":"Photograph: Domenic Lippa","source":"Domenic Lippa","width":"68","height":"68","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987124374/Knockout-007-thumb-9427.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"gu-image-417118798","imageType":"Photograph"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-417118785","relation":"gallery","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987125715/Gill-Shadow-008.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"10 best: Gill Shadow","caption":"<strong>Gill Shadow</strong><br/>Eric Gill designed this quintessentially English font in 1928, produced by the Monotype Corporation. The typeface was inspired by Edward Johnston’s Johnston typeface which was designed for the London Underground. Gill had worked with Johnston and this was his attempt to make the most legible sans serif font. Unlike other more functional sans serifs, Gill was imbued with distinctive characteristics – look at the cap “R”, for instance. Used extensively by many, including the BBC – Gill also made sculptures for the facade of Broadcasting House in London. The variant Gill Shadow stands out as one of the font’s most gloriously idiosyncratic expressions","credit":"Photograph: Domenic Lippa","source":"Domenic Lippa","width":"453","height":"428","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987125715/Gill-Shadow-008.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"gu-image-417118785","imageType":"Photograph"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987125715/Gill-Shadow-008-thumb-1682.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"10 best: Gill Shadow","caption":"<strong>Gill Shadow</strong><br/>Eric Gill designed this quintessentially English font in 1928, produced by the Monotype Corporation. The typeface was inspired by Edward Johnston’s Johnston typeface which was designed for the London Underground. Gill had worked with Johnston and this was his attempt to make the most legible sans serif font. Unlike other more functional sans serifs, Gill was imbued with distinctive characteristics – look at the cap “R”, for instance. Used extensively by many, including the BBC – Gill also made sculptures for the facade of Broadcasting House in London. The variant Gill Shadow stands out as one of the font’s most gloriously idiosyncratic expressions","credit":"Photograph: Domenic Lippa","source":"Domenic Lippa","width":"68","height":"68","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987125715/Gill-Shadow-008-thumb-1682.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"gu-image-417118785","imageType":"Photograph"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-417118804","relation":"gallery","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987127768/Rockwell-009.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"10 best: Rockwell","caption":"<strong>Rockwell</strong><br/>Rockwell is an instantly recognisable slab serif font where the serifs are similar in weight to the horizontal strokes of the letters. Designed by the Monotype foundry’s inhouse design department in 1934, its distinctiveness originates from its geometric form. Although primarily used as a display font, it is the type of font that adds personality to any piece of design. Most typefaces need to be respected and work with your design; however Rockwell is robust enough for you to do things to it. You can pull it apart and clash it together. It has such a great sculptural form but somehow retains its quality","credit":"Photograph: Domenic Lippa","source":"Domenic Lippa","width":"453","height":"428","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987127768/Rockwell-009.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"gu-image-417118804","imageType":"Photograph"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987127768/Rockwell-009-thumb-6446.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"10 best: Rockwell","caption":"<strong>Rockwell</strong><br/>Rockwell is an instantly recognisable slab serif font where the serifs are similar in weight to the horizontal strokes of the letters. Designed by the Monotype foundry’s inhouse design department in 1934, its distinctiveness originates from its geometric form. Although primarily used as a display font, it is the type of font that adds personality to any piece of design. Most typefaces need to be respected and work with your design; however Rockwell is robust enough for you to do things to it. You can pull it apart and clash it together. It has such a great sculptural form but somehow retains its quality","credit":"Photograph: Domenic Lippa","source":"Domenic Lippa","width":"68","height":"68","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987127768/Rockwell-009-thumb-6446.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"gu-image-417118804","imageType":"Photograph"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-417118806","relation":"gallery","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987129075/Sabon-010.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"10 best: Sabon","caption":"<strong>Sabon</strong><br/>Jan Tschichold was a pioneer of modern graphic design. Swiss by birth, Tschichold was active in possibly the most influential period in graphic design history. Between 1947 and 1949 he worked in England where he oversaw the redesign of hundreds of paperbacks for Penguin Books. Most graphic designers do not make good type designers; Tschichold is an exception. He designed several fonts but it’s his 1966 old-style Sabon serif for which he’s most widely known. Based on the typeface Garamond, its uniqueness is that the roman, italic and bold weights are all the same width when typeset","credit":"Photograph: Domenic Lippa","source":"Domenic Lippa","width":"453","height":"428","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987129075/Sabon-010.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"gu-image-417118806","imageType":"Photograph"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987129075/Sabon-010-thumb-9158.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"10 best: Sabon","caption":"<strong>Sabon</strong><br/>Jan Tschichold was a pioneer of modern graphic design. Swiss by birth, Tschichold was active in possibly the most influential period in graphic design history. Between 1947 and 1949 he worked in England where he oversaw the redesign of hundreds of paperbacks for Penguin Books. Most graphic designers do not make good type designers; Tschichold is an exception. He designed several fonts but it’s his 1966 old-style Sabon serif for which he’s most widely known. Based on the typeface Garamond, its uniqueness is that the roman, italic and bold weights are all the same width when typeset","credit":"Photograph: Domenic Lippa","source":"Domenic Lippa","width":"68","height":"68","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/12/1378987129075/Sabon-010-thumb-9158.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"gu-image-417118806","imageType":"Photograph"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-417741026","relation":"thumbnail","type":